Introduction

Cardiovascular Diseases (CVDs)

Cardiovascular diseases (CVDs) are disorders of the heart and blood vessels including coronary heart disease (heart attacks), cerebrovascular diseases (strokes), heart failure (HF), and other types of pathology. Altogether, cardiovascular diseases cause the death of approximately 17 million people worldwide annually. In particular, heart failure occurs when the heart is unable to pump enough blood to the body, and it is usually caused by diabetes, high blood pressure, or other heart conditions or diseases.

Types of Heart Failure

The clinical community groups heart failure into two types based on the ejection fraction value, that is the proportion of blood pumped out of the heart during a single contraction:

  • Heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF): Previously known as heart failure due to left ventricular (LV) systolic dysfunction or systolic heart failure and characterized by an ejection fraction under 40%.
  • Heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (HFpEF): Formerly called diastolic heart failure or heart failure with normal ejection fraction. In this case, the left ventricle contracts normally during systole, but the ventricle is stiff and fails to relax normally during diastole, thus impairing filling.

Ejection fraction is given as a percentage, with physiological values ranging between 50% and 75%.

Disease Progression Evaluation

For the quantitative evaluation of the disease progression, clinicians rely on the New York Heart Association (NYHA) functional classification, which includes four classes:

  • Class I: No symptoms from ordinary activities.
  • Class IV: Any physical activity brings on discomfort, and symptoms occur at rest.

Despite its widespread use, there is no consistent method of assessing the NYHA score, and this classification fails to reliably predict basic features, such as walking distance or exercise tolerance on formal testing.

Challenges in Predicting Heart Failure

Given the importance of a vital organ such as the heart, predicting heart failure has become a priority for medical doctors and physicians. However, to date, predicting heart-failure-related events in clinical practice usually has failed to reach high accuracy.

Machine Learning in Heart Failure Prediction

Machine learning, when applied to medical records, can be an effective tool to:

  1. Predict the survival of each patient with heart failure symptoms.
  2. Detect the most important clinical features (or risk factors) that may lead to heart failure.

Scientists leverage machine learning for both clinical prediction and feature ranking. Computational intelligence has shown its predictive power when applied to medical records. Recent studies on deep learning and meta-analysis have further improved human specialists' performance, albeit with lower accuracy in some cases.

Current Challenges in Modeling Heart Failure

Modeling survival for heart failure and CVDs remains challenging, particularly:

  • Achieving high prediction accuracy.
  • Identifying risk factors.

Most advanced models reach only modest accuracy, with limited interpretability of predicting variables. More recent models show improvements, especially when survival outcomes are coupled with additional targets (e.g., hospitalization).

However, as pointed out by Sakamoto and colleagues, the lack of reproducibility strongly affects model performances, preventing definitive conclusions about the importance of detected factors.

Dataset Overview

We analyzed a dataset containing the medical records of 299 heart failure patients. The patients consisted of 105 women and 194 men, and their ages range between 40 and 95 years old.

Features of the Dataset

The dataset contains 13 features, which report clinical, body, and lifestyle information (Table 1) that we briefly describe here. Some features are binary:

  • Anaemia: A patient is considered to have anaemia if haematocrit levels are lower than 36%.
  • High blood pressure: No definition of high blood pressure is provided in the original dataset.
  • Diabetes, sex, and smoking: Other binary features reported in the dataset.

Key Features Description

  1. Creatinine phosphokinase (CPK): Indicates the level of the CPK enzyme in blood. High levels may suggest heart failure or muscle injury.
  2. Ejection fraction: States the percentage of how much blood the left ventricle pumps out with each contraction.
  3. Serum creatinine: A waste product generated by creatine when a muscle breaks down. High levels may indicate renal dysfunction.
  4. Sodium: A mineral essential for muscle and nerve functioning. Low levels of serum sodium might indicate heart failure.

Target Variable: Death Event

The death event was used as the target variable in our binary classification study. It states whether the patient died or survived before the end of the follow-up period, which lasted 130 days on average.

Dataset Imbalance

  • Survived patients (death event = 0): 203 patients (67.89%).
  • Dead patients (death event = 1): 96 patients (32.11%).

Table 1: Meanings, measurement units, and intervals of each feature of the dataset

Feature Explanation Measurement Range
Age Age of the patient Years [40, ..., 95]
Anaemia Decrease of red blood cells or hemoglobin Boolean 0, 1
High blood pressure If a patient has hypertension Boolean 0, 1
Creatinine phosphokinase Level of the CPK enzyme in the blood mcg/L [23, ..., 7861]
Diabetes If the patient has diabetes Boolean 0, 1
Ejection fraction Percentage of blood leaving the heart at each contraction Percentage [14, ..., 80]
Sex Woman or man Binary 0, 1
Platelets Platelets in the blood kiloplatelets/mL [25.01, ..., 850.00]
Serum creatinine Level of creatinine in the blood mg/dL [0.50, ..., 9.40]
Serum sodium Level of sodium in the blood mEq/L [114, ..., 148]
Smoking If the patient smokes Boolean 0, 1
Time Follow-up period Days [4, ..., 285]
(target) Death event If the patient died during the follow-up period Boolean 0, 1

Note:

  • mcg/L: micrograms per liter
  • mL: microliter
  • mEq/L: milliequivalents per liter

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import altair_ally as aly
from vega_datasets import data

# Enable Vegafusion for better data transformation
aly.alt.data_transformers.enable('vegafusion')

# Load the dataset
file_path = 'data/heart_failure_clinical_records_dataset.csv'
heart_failure_data = pd.read_csv(file_path)

# Define numeric columns
numeric_columns = ['age', 'creatinine_phosphokinase', 'ejection_fraction', 
                   'platelets', 'serum_creatinine', 'serum_sodium', 'time']
# List of binary columns
binary_columns = ['anaemia', 'diabetes', 'high_blood_pressure', 'sex', 'smoking', 'DEATH_EVENT']

# Convert all binary columns to True/False
heart_failure_data[binary_columns] = heart_failure_data[binary_columns].astype(bool)


# Summary statistics
print("Summary Statistics:")
print(heart_failure_data.describe())
